title: PULSAR - Solar Car by Purdue Solar Racing

description.text:
PULSAR is Purdue Solar Racing's award-winning Shell Eco-Marathon Prototype vehicle. PULSAR competed from 2008-2011, and achieved an equivalent efficiency of nearly 5,000 MPG! 
Now you can have your own model of PULSAR for your desk!
For more information on PULSAR and Purdue Solar Racing, visit www.purduesolar.org

You have two options for building this model, either print the full model with support, or print both halves separately and glue them together. Check to make sure that each half is flat against your virtual build surface (sometimes it takes a few tries of the 'Lay Flat' command in replicatorG)

description.text:
Before you exclaim "Really! Does the world need yet another Spherebot design?" Consider the question "How about a Spherebot with a parts cost under $35?" Regardless of the answer, here it is. Is it accurate? Mostly-ish, Sometimes, Not very. Did I mention it was cheap and easy to build.

The bot is arduino powered using a slightly modified version of the Eggduino Firmware by Joachim Cerny making it compatible with the EggBot extensions for Inkscape. (3 cheers for Joachim) A few modifications allow the bot to use the very inexpensive 28byj-48 5v stepper motors and ULN2003 drivers. A TowerPro 9G servo is used to lift and lower a Ultra Fine Sharpie pen. Two 608RS bearings hold the idler arm and a small spring keeps the arm pressed against the sphere. Nerf dart suction cups are used to hold the sphere. It is assembled with M3 machine screws, nuts, washers, the hardware that came with the 9g servo and a small spring from a local hardware store.

The bot is optimized to print on standard 40mm table tennis balls. It is adjustable and could probably print on small eggs.

The video shows a few printing errors since I didn't have the ping pong ball centered well enough and/or have the servo lifting the pen far enough above the ball during some of the moves. This is a work in progress and I might tweak a few things before writing better documentation.

UPDATE 01/08/17
Arduino 1.8.0 compatible firmware source code available from https://github.com/russhughes/EggDuino.

Previous Firmware Modifications

In the EggDuino.ino file around line 40 change the servoPin define to 10:

#define servoPin 10 //Servo

In the EggDuino.ino file around line 50 insert the following function prototypes:

// Function prototypes
void sendAck(void);
void sendError(void);
void loadPenPosFromEE(void);
void storePenUpPosInEE(void);
void storePenDownPosInEE(void);
#define penUpPosEEAddress ((uint16_t *)0) 
#define penDownPosEEAddress ((uint16_t *)2)

In the EggDuino.ino file around line 60 change the AccelStepper declarations to: 

AccelStepper rotMotor(AccelStepper::HALF4WIRE, 2,4,3,5, true);
AccelStepper penMotor(AccelStepper::HALF4WIRE, 6,8,7,9, true);

In the Helper_Functions.ino file around line 96 After the "//set Coordinates and Speed line" add:

rotStepsEBB = map(rotStepsEBB, 0, 3200, 0, 4076);

This will set the scale on the rotation axis to match the one the stepper uses.

Connect the Sphere rotation stepper driver board pins IN1,IN2,IN3 and IN4 to the Arduino pins 2,3,4,5 and the Pen stepper driver board pins IN1,IN2,IN3 and IN4 to the Arduino pins 6,7,8,9. Connect the Pen Servo's signal pin the the Arduino Pin 10.

description.header: Modifications for the Inkscape EggBot Plugin Version 2.7.1
description.text:
The 2.7.1 release of the EggBot extension only looks for the official eggbot board but we can change that pretty easily. Once you have Inkscape and the 2.7.1 EggBot extensions installed. Edit the "ebb_serial.py" file look around line 49 and find the line that reads: 

if port[1].startswith("EiBotBoard"):

and change it to:

if port[1].startswith("EiBotBoard") or port[1].startswith("Arduino"):

Now it should be able to find Arduino's running the EggDuino Firmware.

Next look around line 67 and find the line that reads:

serialPort = serial.Serial( comPort, timeout=1.0 ) # 1 second timeout!

and increase the timeout to 2 or 3 seconds like this:

serialPort = serial.Serial( comPort, timeout=2.0 ) # 2 second timeout or change to 3 if you still can't connect

That should be all that's needed to make it work. It can be a little slow with the increased timeout if you have many COM ports.

description.text:
Kickboard clips as provided by Ikea were too short for the effect I was after so I created these. The clips provided were a fixed length which is fine except that the mounts on the cupboards (they clip on to the feet) are set back differently from the sides compared to the front, to the tune of about 11cm.

They don't need to be structural, just hold themselves together and stop the kickboard from falling over so this was a no-brainer. Printed a couple of these (bit rough as you can see by the photos) but they work fine.

Notes:

Printed with a skirt (5mm) and with settings as above in ABS filament. Infill doesn't need to be bumped up as the perimeters don't permit a lot of infill anyway and everything had structural ribs so it turned out really stable dimensionally - accidentally printed the extension piece upright and it printed fine which I think was a testament to this fact. I would recommend printing it flat however (at least when using FDM) as this orientation lends itself a little better to the end use.

Screw fit

It turned out that I didn't allow enough room for the screws I had laying about.....there was enough in the surrounds however to bore it out a little - including the countersink.

To make sure this was still secure I finished it off with a little superglue so that it didn't fray/split.

After printing you get that red box from second picture. To get what i got you need to add buffers, paint it and add and ballast.
Buffers - i used small nails with 3mm diameter head and 1.5mm diameter shaft that i cut down to size and glued in pre-printed holes. I don't trust printer if it comes to hole diameters so i made those holes for buffers more as mark where to drill than actual holes for assembly.
Paint - I used Castorama branded black matt spray paint but i think any solvent based spray paint or Humbrol enamel will do. Its good to paint it after buffer assembly but before adding ballast.
Ballast - railway modeler's ballast glued with wood glue diluted with water 1:3 or more - same as for ballasting track.

title: My Prusa i3 Plus Feb. 2016 Edition Tweaks

description.text:
[X] references to the image/model with the number X
{U} I designed it, its available here, but its not printed and/or installed.

When I got and assembled my Prusa i3 Plus Feb. 2016 Edition, I recognized the one or other thing I thought you could make better.

The parts are designed so you could use them at assembling, but also to upgrade the assembled printer.

For sure this parts are all printed with my feb 2016 prusa.

  1. When you build the y-axis you should keep 80mm space between the nuts on the threaded rod. Well, you can measure, fix the nuts and later in the progress its not that exact anymore. Because of that you got spacers here. You need 2 times 2 of them you connect with each other on the rod. They keep the 80mm and as long as you hear no cracking plastic and see no gap between them and the nuts you are fine. (IMPORTANT: the .stl file in the package is for 0.4mm nozzles, if you got another one, please install openscad, open the .scad file, change the "nozzle" variable on top, render it and export a new stl file. You may also need to tweak the "flapfactor" variable so your slicer generates the flap correct.) [9-11]

  2. Marrying the portal with the y-axis is a bit tricky, because it is simply not standing :D
    With the portalstand, you need two, you get something to make it stand by itself. Also even if it is not believable with this tiny plastic things, later the vibrations at printing(note the rondings for force redirection) but also the overall stability and precision is increased a lot. They may seem a bit tight at first look and you need force to place them(it may also crack a bit), but they should be very fix. [2-8]

  3. in the tutorial they say one should push the piece of filament until the end of fan shaft. Well you cannot do that, since the hole is simply ending somewhere but not channeling to the fan shaft. This causes problems with the fan holder at printing time. Here you find a 5015housing-MK3.stl with the hole how it should be [12]. If you want to use the tweaked x-carriage I mention below, also use 5015housing-MK3-tweaked.stl [13, 15]

  4. When the x-axis moves it may happen, that a force is applied to the printingfan. In this case the top nose of the x carriage may break. I changed the design a bit. x-carriage-tweaked.stl [14, 15] to use in combination with 5015housing-MK3-tweaked.stl [13, 15]

  5. Whats not written in the guide, after assembly before calibrating z, since now you know everything is straight, you could do an "lcd: settings->auto home"(check the location of z-axis pushbutton before) and check the distance between the delivered, for me orange, plasticpats(see photo) with a caliper. For sure they are not equal. Just turn the nuts on the z-axis threaded rods at the top to adjust. This eases z calibration a lot... for sure only if everything is straight.

  6. the plastic parts for calibrating z could be also tweaked by drawing quartermarks on them. maybe with numbers, so you know exactly which one is which one.

  7. a nice stabilizer reducing the wobbling of the z axis threaded rods you can find here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1425056

title: Ashtray hidden tablet stand. Toyota corolla 2005

description.text:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k_zTgN8aXaI

I made this specially for my toyota corolla 2005.

Tested with Samsung Galaxy Tab A. Should work with many other tablets as well. Galaxy Tab A with a silicone cover and glass screen protector is light pressure fitted, so it doesn't slide out.

Recommended print settings:

Printed in ABS, perhaps it works for PLA too, not sure.

Mirror each piece in your slicer, print in same orientation as shown in the video for best result.

I recommend a brim, heated bed 100C nozzle 235C - or whatever your filament prints best with. Along with kapton tape and ABS juice. Works perfectly for me.

Install instructions:

The file named "Tablet Holder - Holder" should be fused together by applying acetone to the surface that made contact with the buildplate during printing, then press the two pieces together with your hands, while also pressing it up against a table that isn't bumpy. - this will make sure the two pieces align properly. After a minute or two doing this you can release the two pieces and let the acetone dry and fuse the two pieces together.

For final application apply "No more nails 120kg double sided tape" or similar, to the two pieces named "Skinne" you should be able to make out how I applied it from one of the pictures. Then make sure it is inserted and applied correctly into the ashtray, it should not be too high, or else the tray won't close. You'll know what I mean.

Also take note that the tray may open during a bit of acceleration when driving, simple fix is add a tiny piece of "no more nails" to the ashtray piece that prevent the tray from falling out. You can see the tiny piece in the video just as I open the tray, it's red.

description.text:
This arm will help you to shave areas on your body that you cannot reach easily by hand. During pregnancy women like to use this little helper or men who want to have a back free of bodyhair.

You can insert standard razors into the shaving head that is bolted with two knurled screws without any tools. The whole shaving arm is made foldable to fit easily into your luggage.

The arm can also be used as a back scraper. Just design a proper "scraper-head" and attach it to the arm instead of the razor.

In the pictures you see a working prototype. However I recognized some aspects on the prototype that could be improved. Therefore the STL-Files slightly differ from my working example and have those improvements built in. I had no time (and actually no need) for testing the final STL-Files, so I will be very glad if you tell me, whether there are some problems or not.

Simply print out all parts and put them together with M4 screws like shown on the pictures. Carefully clean the locking mechanism after printing.

You should enable support generation as there are some overhanging parts but I tried to reduce them.

title: Touchscreen Display and Rechargeable Battery Pack for the PiKon Telescope / Raspberry Pi

description.text:
In 2014, Mark Wrigley of Alternative Photonics along with Andy King, a Physics and Astronomy research associate at the University of Sheffield, created the PiKon 3d printed telescope. Based on Newton's reflecting telescope design it uses a Raspberry Pi and the PiCamera module, with the camera mounted directly in front of the mirror.

I've always had a curiosity for astronomy, but was never keen enough to invest any money in purchasing the necessary equipment. But when the PiKon project featured in the news it was something that really captured my imagination. A year later in 2015, the PiKon turned to crowdfunding, giving everyone the opportunity to get their hands on one. Be it fully assembled or in a kit form that you can 3d print and assemble yourself, I wasted no time in reserving my perk and was eager to start my build.

My kit arrived in early 2016 and I promptly printed my parts and assembled it. To operate the telescope you use the Raspberry Pi, all of your interactions with the telescope are via the Pi command line interface. This requires you to have access to a TV/monitor and a keyboard, as well as a power source for the Pi and the monitor. This is not a problem if you are operating your PiKon indoors through a window or even if you are out in your back garden, but what if you want to take your PiKon on a field trip to a remote location?

To solve this problem I set about designing and making a small, lightweight and compact all-in-one unit that not only provides power to the Pi, but also includes a display, input controls and a user friendly interface. The result is the TED-VDU, it incorporates the following features:

  • 3d Printed enclosure
  • 2.8" Resistive touchscreen TFT display
  • 5200mAh four cell lithium-ion rechargeable battery
  • A single cable to link the VDU to the PiKon (15-way HD15 cable)
  • Optional 4x programmable (GPIO) buttons
  • Optional LED lights
  • Based on the Cam.py point-and-shoot digital camera user interface

title: ABS Fume Killer
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: ABS fumes are likely not good for you, but sealing off your Thingomatic so that it's impractical to use is not too great either. This parametric design is a halfway house, it filters most of the fumes through activated charcoal using a 200mm computer fan and variable speed controller. The filter is located at the back, and the sides and top are covered with clear lexan sheet and thumbscrews. This serves to only allow air to enter through the front and allows access through the front. Remember to replace your activated charcoal every few weeks, a lot of air is being pulled through so it will get used up fast. Adjust the fan speed controller, you want the fan at a slow speed, just fast enough to pull the air through. The faster the fan is, the less time the air is in contact with the charcoal and the less effective it will be. You can test air is being pulled through by using an incense stick or draft test stick. This is my first design, so it's less than perfect (particularly in the segmentation), but it does work and can be assembled. Improvements that could be made is the way that the parts join together. Also occasionally the filament is bent when the Z axis is zero'd to the top, although this doesn't cause any issues for me. Fan Speed Controller: http://pcbheaven.com/circuitpages/PWM_Fan_controller_using_a_555 Thumb Screws can be found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9094

• - Cut lexan to cover sides and top. Print thumbscrews and insert M3 nuts. Drill holes and attach lexan and M3 thumbscrews
  • - Do the same with the top, but drill a hole directly above the extruder filament hole just slightly bigger than the filament. Your filament is thread through this hole
  • - Print out the 9 parts for the case and glue together with some filament dissolved in acetone. Join the outside parts and let dry before gluing supports
  • - Print out the 4 parts for the filter and glue together with some of the acetone / filament mixture
  • - Attach the furnace filter material to both sides of the filter with hot glue
  • - Fill filter completely with activated charcoal through the fill hole. Tap on a surface to settle and top up again. Then seal with tape.
  • - Put filter in the fume killer case, and attach fan with mounting screws
  • - Attach fume killer to the back of the ToM with bolts / screws (you'll need to drill mounting holes in the fume killer and ToM)
  • - Attach controller to fan and adjust fan

A laser cutted shadow throwing lamp in the shape of a dodecahedron made out of 3mm plywood. The description of the project can be found here https://fablab-wuerzburg.de/projekte/dodekaeder-lampe.
For the light source a 10W halogen lamp is used. Because lamp sockets differs you have to design your own socket. In "lamp_socket.dxf" is a prototype.

You need to cut only all the "all_parts_X"-dxf files, if you don't want to change the design. Therefore you need a laser cutter with a working area of minimum 500mm x 300mm.

If you want to redesign some parts, dxf-files of all single parts are also uploaded.
Here is a list of the number of the single parts you have to cut.

  • 11x "face.dxf"
  • 1x "bottom.dxf"
  • 5x "base.dxf"
  • 100x "joint_face_face.dxf"
  • 20x "joint_face_bottom.dxf"
  • 5x "joint_base_base.dxf"
  • 1x "lamp_socket.dxf" or modified lamp socket

I should mention that the light source should be as small as possible to obtain a sharp shadow

Eldritch Horror has enough expansions now that everything will not fit in one box. If the only expansions you have are Forsaken Lore and Mountains of Madness, I have made a single box solution that will fit.

This organizer will fit Eldritch Horror and the Forsaken Lore, Mountains of Madness, Strange Remnants, Under the Pyramids, Signs of Carcosa, and the Dreamlands expansions. It is a tight fit at this point and you may want to add a separate condition card organizer (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:989153) to keep things neat.

This will likely have to be revisited when/if they put out a new expansion, but it still works for now.

Box A:

Fits all cards excluding the player (large), ancient ones (large), and small cards that are not conditions.
Also fits one of the side boards.
The vertical holders are for the ancient ones decks. I sized them for specific AOs (see pdf):
A-G1: Abhoth, Azathoth, Cthulhu, and Elder Things
A-G2: Ithaqua, Nephren-Ka, Shub-Niggurath + a spare
A-G3: Syzygy, Yig, Yog-Sothoth + a spare

You will need to print 4 copies of the condition card holders.
Divide the remaining cards however you like.

Box B:
I have included a PDF of the layout for this box as well.
This box fits the main board as well as a side board. Make sure the small cards tray is oriented with the high wall toward the middle of the box to keep the side board from moving around.

This build took me about a spool and a half to print and about a week.

This is the set of non-transitive dice invented by Bradley Efron.

Red die: 4,4,4,4,0,0
Yellow die: 3,3,3,3,3,3
Green die: 6,6,2,2,2,2
Blue die: 5,5,5,1,1,1.

Two players choose a die each, cast them, and the player who gets the highest number is the winner. What is special about these dice is that none of them is the best. For each die there is another that beats it with a probability of 2/3. In this case red beats yellow, yellow beats green, green beats blue and blue beats red.

So, contrary to intuition, the player with the advantage is the one who chooses die second. Useful to show this unexpected property with a game. More info in https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nontransitive_dice.
